":"Woodchurch, Kent, England"},"cs":{"1178–1198":"1178–1198","1180–1218":"1180–1218","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1158–1178":"1158–1178","1163–1198":"1163–1198","before 1178":"před 1178","1158":"1158","1178":"1178","before 1198":"před 1198","1198":"1198","1163":"1163","about 1198":"okolo 1198","1260":"1260","1218":"1218","1180":"1180","Wakehurst, Kent, England":"Kent, Anglie, United Kingdom","England":"Anglie","Kent, England":"Kent, Anglie, United Kingdom","Woodchurch, Kent, England":"Woodchurch, Kent, Anglie"},"da":{"1178–1198":"1178–1198","1180–1218":"1180–1218","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1158–1178":"1158–1178","1163–1198":"1163–1198","before 1178":"før 1178","1158":"1158","1178":"1178","before 1198":"før 1198","1198":"1198","1163":"1163","about 1198":"omkring 1198","1260":"1260","1218":"1218","1180":"1180","Wakehurst, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Woodchurch, Kent, England":"Woodchurch, Kent, England"},"nl":{"1178–1198":"1178–1198","1180–1218":"1180–1218","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1158–1178":"1158–1178","1163–1198":"1163–1198","before 1178":"vóór 1178","1158":"1158","1178":"1178","before 1198":"vóór 1198","1198":"1198","1163":"1163","about 1198":"circa 1198","1260":"1260","1218":"1218","1180":"1180","Wakehurst, Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Woodchurch, Kent, England":"Woodchurch, Kent, England"},"en":{"1178–1198":"1178–1198","1180–1218":"1180–1218","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1158–1178":"1158–1178","1163–1198":"1163–1198","before 1178":"before 1178","1158":"1158","1178":"1178","before 1198":"before 1198","1198":"1198","1163":"1163","about 1198":"about 1198","1260":"1260","1218":"1218","1180":"1180","Wakehurst, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Woodchurch, Kent, England":"Woodchurch, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wakehurst","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Wakehurst Place in Ardingly (Sussex)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Rici","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Richard  , or, less frequently, of   Frederick   or other names ending in <i>-ric(k)</i>. It is also used as an independent given name, especially in North America."],"variants":[{"name":"Richard","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Rici Wakehurst was born in 1178, in Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Wakehurst, was 20 and his mother, Mrs Wakehurst, was 16. He married Lady Wakehurst of Kent before 1198, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1198, in his hometown, at the age of 20, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1178–1198":"1178–1198","1180–1218":"1180–1218","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1158–1178":"1158–1178","1163–1198":"1163–1198","before 1178":"enne 1178","1158":"1158","1178":"1178","before 1198":"enne 1198","1198":"1198","1163":"1163","about 1198":"umbes 1198","1260":"1260","1218":"1218","1180":"1180","Wakehurst, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, E